@node main "Introduction"
@font helvetica.font 13

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}
				A brief introduction....
@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

"@{b}AddItem@{ub}"  was  designed  after  the  request  of one user who owns a "@{b}Draco@{ub}" Computer (C. Davies). He had
problems  to  start  programs with various program launchers, e.g. the original "@{b}FKey@{ub}" program. Most launched
programs, he said, terminate with a message: "Can't access file....".
After  Mr.  Berson who is helping Mr. Davies to produce Video sequences reported me that I started to write a
utility  called  "@{b}AddItem@{ub}".  This  utility only adds 'items' into the Workbench tool menu and since it should work
on  a  "@{b}Draco@{ub}"  Computer,  it  only  uses  the  official  way  to  add  and  remove these 'items'. Version one of
"@{b}AddItem@{ub}" was written by me in a day or so and then given to Mr. Davies.
He  tried it and said it worked well, until he got installed that new program which failed with: "Can't access file
@{b}PROGDIR:@{ub}....  ".  "What  the  hell  happened?"  I  asked  myself,  till  I  read  (once  again)  the  AMIGA  OS 2
documentation.  @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub}  is  an invention of AMIGA OS 2, which is only the home directory of a program. It
is used when a program attempts to read a file in its home-dir. Instead of:

CD0:Graphic/Raytracers/SuperRayTrace/loaders/jpec

it can access the file jpec via:

PROGDIR:loaders/jpec

since the system will initialise @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub} with "CD0:Graphic/Raytracers/SuperRayTrace".

Because   "@{b}AddItem@{ub}"   only  launched  the  programs  via  DOS-function  Execute()  only  a  ChangeDir  was
performed. To set up the @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub} something more had to be done.

Mr.  Berson  gave  me  a  tip.  "Why",  he  asked,  "don't you launch the programs as they where started from
Workbench".

After  thinking  about a solution (I thought emulating a WB start is a difficult thing) I came to the conclusion that
Mr. Berson was right, emulating a WB start is the only thing that helps.

So "@{b}AddItem 2@{ub}" was born. I took about another day to finish it.

After  several  inventions  (mainly  better  fault  handling) I gave it to Mr. Davies. Since that day he never had
problems again with any program launched by "@{b}AddItem 2@{ub}".


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


"AddItem 2" supports three types of program launching:

[1] Execute as single program as the program was started from @{"Shell" link Shell}
[2] Execute as single program as the program was started from @{"Shell with argument" link ShellAndArgs}
[3] Execute as single program as the program was started from @{"Workbench" link Workbench}


@endnode

